# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: trpc-typesafe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:trpc-typesafe/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] RPC is short for "Remote Procedure Call".
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] It is a way of calling functions on one computer (the server) from another computer (the client).
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] With traditional HTTP/REST APIs, you call a URL and get a response.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] With RPC, you call a function and get a response.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] tRPC (TypeScript Remote Procedure Call) is one implementation of RPC, designed for TypeScript monorepos.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] It has its own flavor, but is RPC at its heart.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] If you inspect the network traffic of a tRPC app, you'll see that it's fairly standard HTTP requests and responses, but you don't need to think about the implementation details while writing your application code.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] You call functions, and tRPC takes care of everything else.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] You should ignore details like HTTP Verbs, since they carry meaning in REST APIs but, in RPC, form part of your function names instead, for instance: `getUser(id)` instead of `GET /users/:id`.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] Below are some terms that are used frequently in the tRPC ecosystem.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] We'll be using these throughout the documentation, so it's good to get familiar with them.
[src:trpc-typesafe/concepts] Most of these concepts also have their own pages in the documentation.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The **`Promise`** object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] To learn about the way promises work and how you can use them, we advise you to read Using promises first.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] A `Promise` is a proxy for a value not necessarily known when the promise is created.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] It allows you to associate handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual success value or failure reason.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] This lets asynchronous methods return values like synchronous methods: instead of immediately returning the final value, the asynchronous method returns a *promise* to supply the value at some point in the future.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The *eventual state* of a pending promise can either be *fulfilled* with a value or *rejected* with a reason (error).
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] When either of these options occur, the associated handlers queued up by a promise's `then` method are called.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] If the promise has already been fulfilled or rejected when a corresponding handler is attached, the handler will be called, so there is no race condition between an asynchronous operation completing and its handlers being attached.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] A promise is said to be *settled* if it is either fulfilled or rejected, but not pending.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] (Flowchart showing how the Promise state transitions between pending, fulfilled, and rejected via then/catch handlers.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] A pending promise can become either fulfilled or rejected.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] If fulfilled, the "on fulfillment" handler, or first parameter of the then() method, is executed and carries out further asynchronous actions.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] You will also hear the term *resolved* used with promises — this means that the promise is settled or "locked-in" to match the eventual state of another promise, and further resolving or rejecting it has no effect.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The States and fates document from the original Promise proposal contains more details about promise terminology.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Colloquially, "resolved" promises are often equivalent to "fulfilled" promises, but as illustrated in "States and fates", resolved promises can be pending or rejected as well.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] This promise is already *resolved* at the time when it's created (because the `resolveOuter` is called synchronously), but it is resolved with another promise, and therefore won't be *fulfilled* until 1 second later, when the inner promise fulfills.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] In practice, the "resolution" is often done behind the scenes and not observable, and only its fulfillment or rejection are.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] `Promise` itself has no first-class protocol for cancellation, but you may be able to directly cancel the underlying asynchronous operation, typically using `AbortController`.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The promise methods `then()`, `catch()`, and `finally()` are used to associate further action with a promise that becomes settled.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method takes up to two arguments; the first argument is a callback function for the fulfilled case of the promise, and the second argument is a callback function for the rejected case.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The `catch()` and `finally()` methods call `then()` internally and make error handling less verbose.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] For example, a `catch()` is really just a `then()` without passing the fulfillment handler.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] As these methods return promises, they can be chained.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] We will use the following terminology: *initial promise* is the promise on which `then` is called; *new promise* is the promise returned by `then`.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The two callbacks passed to `then` are called *fulfillment handler* and *rejection handler*, respectively.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The settled state of the initial promise determines which handler to execute.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The completion of the handler determines the settled state of the new promise.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] For example, in the code above, if `myPromise` rejects, `handleRejectedA` will be called, and if `handleRejectedA` completes normally (without throwing or returning a rejected promise), the promise returned by the first `then` will be fulfilled instead of staying rejected.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Therefore, if an error must be handled immediately, but we want to maintain the error state down the chain, we must throw an error of some type in the rejection handler.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] On the other hand, in the absence of an immediate need, we can leave out error handling until the final `catch()` handler.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Each time, JavaScript picks a job from the queue and executes it to completion.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The jobs are defined by the executor of the `Promise()` constructor, the handlers passed to `then`, or any platform API that returns a promise.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The promises in a chain represent the dependency relationship between these jobs.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] When a promise settles, the respective handlers associated with it are added to the back of the job queue.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] A promise can participate in more than one chain.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] For the following code, the fulfillment of `promiseA` will cause both `handleFulfilled1` and `handleFulfilled2` to be added to the job queue.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Because `handleFulfilled1` is registered first, it will be invoked first.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] An action can be assigned to an already settled promise.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] In this case, the action is added immediately to the back of the job queue and will be performed when all existing jobs are completed.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Therefore, an action for an already "settled" promise will occur only after the current synchronous code completes and at least one loop-tick has passed.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] This guarantees that promise actions are asynchronous.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The JavaScript ecosystem had made multiple Promise implementations long before it became part of the language.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Despite being represented differently internally, at the minimum, all Promise-like objects implement the *Thenable* interface.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] A thenable implements the `.then()` method, which is called with two callbacks: one for when the promise is fulfilled, one for when it's rejected.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] To interoperate with the existing Promise implementations, the language allows using thenables in place of promises.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] For example, `Promise.resolve` will not only resolve promises, but also trace thenables.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method is responsible for scheduling the execution of the provided `onFulfilled` and `onRejected` callbacks.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Its semantics, including error handling and asynchronicity, are precisely defined in the Promises/A+ specification, and we shall not repeat them here.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] It's very rare that you need to implement a thenable yourself; even if you are not using native promises, you would probably be using a Promise library such as Bluebird.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **all** of the promises fulfill; rejects when **any** of the promises rejects.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **any** of the promises fulfills; rejects when **all** of the promises reject.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] Settles when **any** of the promises settles.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] In other words, fulfills when any of the promises fulfills; rejects when any of the promises rejects.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] All these methods take an iterable of promises (thenables, to be exact) and return a new promise.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] They all support subclassing, which means they can be called on subclasses of `Promise`, and the result will be a promise of the subclass type.
[src:trpc-typesafe/global-objects-promise] To do so, the subclass's constructor must implement the same signature as the `Promise()` constructor — accepting a single `executor` function that can be called with the `resolve` and `reject` callbacks as parameters.
